hort description|Egyptian footballer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Mido\n| image          = Mido 18-10-2008 1.jpg\n| image_size     = 200px\n| caption        = Mido in 2008\n| fullname       = Ahmed Hossam Hussein Abdelhamid<ref name=\"Mido\">{{Cite web\n| title = Mido\n| url = https://int.soccerway.com/players/ahmed-abdelhamid-hossam/4464/\n| publisher = Soccerway\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012}}</ref>\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1983|2|23|df=y}}<ref name=\"Mido\"/>\n| birth_place    = [[Cairo]], Egypt\n| height         = 1.88 m<ref name=\"Mido\"/>\n| position       = [[Forward (association football)|Striker]]\n| currentclub    = \n| youthyears1    = 1990\u20131999\n| youthclubs1    = [[Zamalek SC|Zamalek]]\n| years1         = 1999\u20132000\n| years2         = 2000\u20132001\n| years3         = 2001\u20132003\n| years4         = 2003\n| years5         = 2003\u20132004\n| years6         = 2004\u20132006\n| years7         = 2005\u20132006\n| years8         = 2006\u20132007\n| years9         = 2007\u20132010\n| years10        = 2009\n| years11        = 2009\u20132010\n| years12        = 2010\n| years13        = 2010\n| years14        = 2011\u20132012\n| years15        = 2012\u20132013\n| clubs1         = [[Zamalek SC|Zamalek]]\n| clubs2         = [[K.A.A. Gent|Gent]]\n| clubs3         = [[AFC Ajax|Ajax]]\n| clubs4         = \u2192 [[Celta de Vigo|Celta Vigo]] (loan)\n| clubs5         = [[Olympique de Marseille|Marseille]]\n| clubs6         = [[A.S. Roma|Roma]]\n| clubs7         = \u2192 [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] (loan)\n| clubs8         = [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]]\n| clubs9         = [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]]\n| clubs10        = \u2192 [[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]] (loan)\n| clubs11        = \u2192 [[Zamalek SC|Zamalek]] (loan)\n| clubs12        = \u2192 [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] (loan)\n| clubs13        = \u2192 [[AFC Ajax|Ajax]] (loan)\n| clubs14        = [[Zamalek SC|Zamalek]]\n| clubs15        = [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]]\n| caps1          = 4\n| caps2          = 21\n| caps3          = 40\n| caps4          = 8\n| caps5          = 22\n| caps6          = 8\n| caps7          = 36\n| caps8          = 12\n| caps9          = 25\n| caps10         = 12\n| caps11         = 15\n| caps12         = 9\n| caps13         = 5\n| caps14         = 3\n| caps15         = 1\n| goals1         = 3\n| goals2         = 11\n| goals3         = 21\n| goals4         = 4\n| goals5         = 7\n| goals6         = 0\n| goals7         = 13\n| goals8         = 1\n| goals9         = 6\n| goals10        = 2\n| goals11        = 1\n| goals12        = 0\n| goals13        = 2\n| goals14        = 2\n| goals15        = 0\n| totalcaps      = 221\n| totalgoals     = 73\n| nationalyears1 = 1999\u20132001\n| nationalyears2 = 2001\u20132009\n| nationalteam1  = [[Egypt national under-20 football team|Egypt U20]]\n| nationalteam2  = [[Egypt national football team|Egypt]]\n| nationalcaps1  = 13\n| nationalcaps2  = 51\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n| nationalgoals2 = 20\n| manageryears1  = 2014\n| managerclubs1  = [[Zamalek SC|Zamalek]]\n| manageryears2  = 2015\n| managerclubs2  = [[Ismaily SC|Ismaily]]\n| manageryears3  = 2016\n| managerclubs3  = [[Zamalek SC|Zamalek]]\n| manageryears4  = 2016\u20132017\n| managerclubs4  = [[Wadi Degla SC|Wadi Degla]]\n| manageryears5  = 2018\u20132019\n| managerclubs5  = [[Al-Wehda Club (Mecca)|Al Wehda]]\n| manageryears6  = 2019\u20132020\n| managerclubs6  = [[Misr Lel Makkasa SC|El Makkasa]]\n| medaltemplates = {{MedalCountry|{{fb|EGY}}}}\n{{MedalSport|Men's [[association football|football]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Africa Cup of Nations]]}}\n{{Medal|W|[[2006 Africa Cup of Nations|2006 Egypt]]|}}\n}}\n'''Ahmed Hossam Hussein Abdelhamid''' ({{lang-ar|\u0623\u062d\u0645\u062f \u062d\u0633\u0627\u0645 \u062d\u0633\u064a\u0646 \u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u062d\u0645\u064a\u062f}}; born 23 February 1983), publicly known as '''Mido''', is an Egyptian former [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Forward (association football)|striker]], and a current [[Manager (association football)|manager]].\n\nMido started his career with [[Zamalek SC|Zamalek]] in Egypt in 1999. He left the club for [[K.A.A. Gent|Gent]] of [[Belgium]] in 2000, where he won the [[Belgian Ebony Shoe]]. This led to a move to Dutch side [[AFC Ajax|Ajax]] in 2001, from where he joined [[Celta de Vigo|Celta Vigo]] on [[Loan (sports)|loan]] in 2003. His next destination was [[Olympique de Marseille|Marseille]] in France and he left them for Italian side [[A.S. Roma|Roma]] in 2004. He joined English side [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] on an 18-month loan in 2005 and eventually joined the club permanently in 2006. He left the club in 2007 to join Middlesbrough, from whom he joined [[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]], [[Zamalek SC|Zamalek]], [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] and Ajax on loan. In 2011, he rejoined Zamalek, before joining Barnsley in 2012. He also played for [[Egypt national football team|Egypt]] 51 times, scoring 20 goals. Mido retired from football in June 2013.\n\n==Club career==\n\n===Zamalek===\nBorn in [[Cairo]], Mido started his career with [[Egyptian Premier League]] club [[Zamalek SC|Zamalek]] in 1999.<ref name=\"Hossam, Ahmed 'Mido'\">{{NFT player\n| pid = 2067\n| name = Hossam, Ahmed 'Mido'\n| accessdate = 17 August 2007}}</ref> He made his league debut on 22 May 2000 in a 0\u20130 draw against El Qanah.<ref name=\"Zamalek Soccer Games 1999/2000\">{{cite web\n| url = http://www.angelfire.com/ak/EgyptianSports/ZamalekLeagueGames9900.html\n| title = Zamalek Soccer Games 1999/2000\n| publisher = Angelfire\n| accessdate = 21 January 2011}}</ref> The next week, Mido scored his first two goals against [[Aluminium Nag Hamm\u00e2di]], which Zamalek won 3\u20132.<ref name=\"Grand they were\">\n{{cite news\n| first = Alaa\n| last = Shahine\n| title = Grand they were\n| url = http://weekly.ahram.org.eg/2000/485/sprt1.htm\n| newspaper = Al-Ahram Weekly\n| location = Cairo\n| date = 8 June 2000\n| accessdate = 21 January 2011\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110402062200/http://weekly.ahram.org.eg/2000/485/sprt1.htm\n| archivedate = 2 April 2011\n| url-status = dead\n}}\n</ref> His African debut came on 28 May 2000, in a 2\u20131 win against [[Ethiopian Coffee FC|Ethiopian Coffee]], making the aggregate score 3\u20133, which led to the game being decided on penalties. Zamalek won 4\u20132.<ref name=\"Giants Zamalek fail to ground Coffee\">{{cite news\n| title = Giants Zamalek fail to ground Coffee\n| url = http://www.iol.co.za/sport/giants-zamalek-fail-to-ground-coffee-1.338905\n| newspaper = Independent Online (South Africa)\n| date = 7 May 2000\n| accessdate = 21 January 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Blitzkrieg in Ismailia\">\n{{cite news\n| first = Abeer\n| last = Anwar\n| title = Blitzkrieg in Ismailia\n| url = http://weekly.ahram.org.eg/2000/481/sprt7.htm\n| newspaper = Al-Ahram Weekly\n| location = Cairo\n| accessdate = 21 January 2011\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110605055223/http://weekly.ahram.org.eg/2000/481/sprt7.htm\n| archivedate = 5 June 2011\n| url-status = dead\n}}\n</ref> Zamalek eventually reached the [[2000 African Cup Winners' Cup]] final, beating Cameroonian side [[Canon Yaound\u00e9]] 4\u20133 on aggregate.<ref name=\"The big turnaround\">{{cite news\n |title=The big turnaround \n |first=Abeer \n |last=Anwar \n |url=http://weekly.ahram.org.eg/2000/510/sp3.htm \n |newspaper=Al-Ahram Weekly \n |accessdate=21 January 2011 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110124222201/http://weekly.ahram.org.eg/2000/510/sp3.htm \n |archivedate=24 January 2011 \n}}</ref><ref name=\"On par with the greats\">\n{{cite news\n| title = On par with the greats\n| first = Abeer\n| last = Anwar\n| url = http://weekly.ahram.org.eg/2000/512/sp1.htm\n| newspaper = Al-Ahram Weekly\n| accessdate = 21 January 2011\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110123025711/http://weekly.ahram.org.eg/2000/512/sp1.htm\n| archivedate = 23 January 2011\n| url-status = dead\n}}\n</ref> Mido's performances eventually attracted interest from Belgian club [[K.A.A. Gent|Gent]].<ref name=\"Hossam, Ahmed 'Mido'\"/>\n\n===Gent===\nIn 2000, at the age of 17, Mido signed for Gent.<ref name=\"Hossam, Ahmed 'Mido'\"/><ref>{{Cite news\n| first = Amr\n| last = Shaheen\n| title = Zamalek win big payout\n| url = http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/africa/3001885.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 3 May 2003\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012}}</ref> Initially, he suffered from homesickness, and returned to Egypt shortly after arriving in Belgium, only staying at his father's vehement insistence. Working hard to fight his reservations, Mido eventually overcame them, in his own words gaining \"the mentality of a pro\". Gent manager [[Patrick Remy (footballer)|Patrick Remy]] was impressed by Mido's handling of the issue and promoted him to the first team in September 2000, placing him at first on the substitutes' bench. However, Mido continued to impress Remy, who commented on his \"responsibilities ... [and] great technical capabilities\".<ref name=\"Portrait of a young pro\"/> He eventually became a first-team regular, and made his league debut on 27 August 2000 in a 4\u20131 away win against [[V.C. Eendracht Aalst 2002|Eendracht Aalst]]. On 2 October 2000, he scored his first goal in a 2\u20131 home win against [[Standard Li\u00e8ge]]. His European debut came on 12 September 2000, where Gent suffered a 6\u20130 home defeat to [[AFC Ajax|Ajax]]. He became a fan favourite, and was praised by the Belgian press at the end of the season. Mido went on to win the [[Belgian Ebony Shoe]] in 2001 as the best African player in the [[Belgian Pro League|Belgian First Division]], as well as being named the Belgian \"Discovery of the Year\". As he attracted interest from major clubs both in Belgium and abroad, he ended the season with a powerful performance against [[Royal Antwerp F.C.|Royal Antwerp]], scoring one of Gent's goals in a 3\u20131 win and setting up the other two. Two years later, Remy described the match to an Egyptian journalist, saying that \"Mido did everything.\"<ref name=\"Portrait of a young pro\">\n{{cite news\n| title = Grand they were\n| first = Nashwa\n| last = Abdel-Tawab\n| url = http://weekly.ahram.org.eg/2003/668/sp7.htm\n| newspaper = Al-Ahram Weekly\n| date = 11 December 2003\n| accessdate = 28 November 2011\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20130327092226/http://weekly.ahram.org.eg/2003/668/sp7.htm\n| archivedate = 27 March 2013\n| url-status = dead\n}}\n</ref> He finished the season with 11 goals from 21 matches, as Gent finished fifth, earning them a spot in the following season of the [[2001 UEFA Intertoto Cup|UEFA Intertoto Cup]].<ref name=\"Une \u00e9baine pour Kompany\">{{cite news\n| title = Une \u00e9baine pour Kompany\n| url = http://sport.be.msn.com/fr/jupilerproleague/nieuws/article.html?Article_ID=41423\n| work = Sport\n| date = 7 May 2004\n| accessdate = 21 January 2011\n| language = French\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120315180525/http://sport.be.msn.com/fr/jupilerproleague/nieuws/article.html?Article_ID=41423\n| archive-date = 15 March 2012\n| url-status = dead\n}}</ref>\n\n===Ajax===\nAfter his success in Belgium with Gent, Mido signed a five-year contract with [[Eredivisie]] team [[AFC Ajax|Ajax]] in 2001.<ref name=\"Egypt's new star rises\">{{cite news\n| title = Egypt's new star rises\n| url = http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/africa/1371798.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 5 June 2001\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012}}</ref> He suffered a concussion during their [[UEFA Europa League|UEFA Cup]] match with [[Apollon Limassol|Limassol]], after colliding with a [[Defender (association football)|defender]].<ref name=\"Ajax fear over Mido injury\">{{Cite news\n| first = Jeffrey\n| last = Glorie\n| title = Ajax fear over Mido injury\n| url = http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11913/2219766/\n| publisher = Sky Sports\n| date = 1 October 2001\n| accessdate = 29 June 2012}}</ref> He made his return for the team against [[SC Heerenveen|Heerenveen]], a match which Ajax lost 5\u20131.<ref name=\"First defeat for Ajax\">\n{{cite news\n| title = First defeat for Ajax\n| url = http://egyptianplayers.com/archive/mido/articles-mido-24-10-2001.htm\n| publisher = Egyptian Players\n| date = 24 October 2001\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012\n}}{{Dead link|date=April 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n</ref> However, he was sent off against [[FC Twente|Twente]], after kicking [[Spira Gruji\u0107]] whilst trying to beat him to the ball, for which he was later given a three-match ban.<ref name=\"Mido sent off in Ajax Vs Twente Match\">\n{{cite news\n| title = Mido sent off in Ajax Vs Twente Match\n| url = http://egyptianplayers.com/archive/mido/articles-mido--28-11-2001.htm\n| publisher = Egyptian Players\n| date = 28 November 2001\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012\n}}{{Dead link|date=April 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n</ref><ref name=\"Three-match ban for Mido\">{{Cite news\n| first = Jeffrey\n| last = Glorie\n| title = Three-match ban for Mido\n| url = http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11913/2224275/\n| publisher = Sky Sports\n| date = 4 December 2001\n| accessdate = 29 June 2012}}</ref> He returned for Ajax against [[Vitesse Arnhem|Vitesse]], coming on as a [[Substitute (association football)|substitute]] in the 75th minute.<ref name=\"Mido participated in Ajax-Vitesse match\">\n{{cite news\n| title = Mido participated in Ajax-Vitesse match\n| url = http://egyptianplayers.com/archive/mido/articles-mido--20-12-2001.htm\n| publisher = Egyptian Players\n| date = 20 December 2001\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012\n}}{{Dead link|date=April 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n</ref> He failed to be selected for the substitutes bench against [[Feyenoord]] in March 2002,<ref name=\"Mido wasn't selected for Ajax-Feyenoord match\">\n{{cite news\n| title = Mido wasn't selected for Ajax-Feyenoord match\n| url = http://egyptianplayers.com/archive/mido/articles-mido--3-3-2002.htm\n| publisher = Egyptian Players\n| date = 3 March 2002\n| accessdate = 17 August 2007\n}}{{Dead link|date=April 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n</ref> which was due to a minor clash with manager [[Ronald Koeman]], and Mido left for a short vacation in Cairo.<ref name=\"Egypt's Mido still with Ajax\">{{cite news\n| title = Egypt's Mido still with Ajax\n| url = http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/1856429.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 5 March 2002\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012}}</ref> Mido scored in Ajax's victory over [[FC Utrecht|Utrecht]] in the [[KNVB Cup]] final, meaning he ended the 2001\u201302 season with the Dutch League and Cup double.<ref name=\"Ajax seal double with last gasp strikes\">{{Cite news\n| first = Patrick\n| last = Goss\n| title = Ajax seal double with last gasp strikes\n| url = http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11913/2236880/\n| publisher = Sky Sports\n| date = 12 May 2002\n| accessdate = 29 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nHe played for only 32 minutes against [[FC Groningen|Groningen]], after a display which lacked creativity.<ref name=\"Mido played for 32 minutes against Groningen\">\n{{Cite news\n| title = Mido played for 32 minutes against FC Groningen\n| url = http://egyptianplayers.com/archive/mido/articles-mido-1-9-2002.htm\n| publisher = Egyptian Players\n| date = 1 September 2002\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012\n}}{{Dead link|date=April 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n</ref> He said afterwards he was tired and was carrying a slight injury during the match, but Koeman criticised Mido saying he was not giving everything.<ref name=\"Mido told Dutch TV: I was very tired and slightly injured\">\n{{Cite news\n| title = Mido told Dutch TV: I was very tired and slightly injured\n| url = http://egyptianplayers.com/archive/mido/articles-mido-5-9-2002.htm\n| publisher = Egyptian Players\n| date = 5 September 2002\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012\n}}{{Dead link|date=April 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n</ref> He revealed in September 2002 that he wanted to leave Ajax in the transfer window in late December.<ref name=\"Mido reveals Ajax exit plan\">{{Cite news\n| first = Gerrit\n| last = van Leeuwen\n| title = Mido reveals Ajax exit plan\n| url = http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11913/2245301/\n| publisher = Sky Sports\n| date = 14 September 2002\n| accessdate = 29 June 2012}}</ref> However, Mido soon apologised to Koeman and [[Leo Beenhakker]] regarding the transfer comments,<ref name=\"Mido issues apology\">{{Cite news\n| first = Gerrit\n| last = van Leeuwen\n| title = Mido issues apology\n| url = http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11913/2245188/\n| publisher = Sky Sports\n| date = 16 September 2002\n| accessdate = 29 June 2012}}</ref> saying he was \"irresponsible\" and \"unthoughtful\". He was handed a fine and suspended from Ajax's game against [[Olympique Lyonnais]].<ref name=\"Mido Vs Koeman- The Full Story\">\n{{cite news\n| title = Mido Vs Koeman- The Full Story\n| url = http://egyptianplayers.com/archive/mido/articles-mido-16-9-2002.htm\n| publisher = Egyptian Players\n| date = 16 September 2002\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012\n}}{{Dead link|date=April 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n</ref> In December of that year, he revealed that he wanted to stay at Ajax.<ref name=\"Mido pledges future to Ajax\">{{Cite news\n| first = Alex\n| last = Livie\n| title = Mido pledges future to Ajax\n| url = http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11913/2252455/\n| publisher = Sky Sports\n| date = 17 December 2002\n| accessdate = 29 June 2012}}</ref> He scored for Ajax during their 6\u20130 defeat of [[Willem II (football club)|Willem II]] in February 2003,<ref name=\"Ajax cruise to win\">{{Cite news\n| first = Alex\n| last = Livie\n| title = Ajax cruise to win\n| url = http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11913/2256580/\n| publisher = Sky Sports\n| date = 2 February 2003\n| accessdate = 29 June 2012}}</ref> but Koeman again criticised Mido, commenting negatively on his performance against [[Roda JC|Roda]] in the KNVB Cup.<ref name=\"Koeman Comments on Mido's performance\">\n{{Cite news\n| title = Koeman Comments on Mido's performance\n| url = http://egyptianplayers.com/archive/mido/articles-mido-8-2-2003.htm\n| publisher = Egyptian Players\n| date = 8 February 2003\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012\n}}{{Dead link|date=April 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n</ref> He was dropped for Ajax's next game against Feyenoord, only featuring as an unused substitute.<ref name=\"Ajax Vs Feyenoord\">\n{{Cite news\n| title = Ajax Vs Feyenoord\n| url = http://egyptianplayers.com/archive/mido/articles-mido-9-2-2003.htm\n| publisher = Egyptian Players\n| date = 9 February 2003\n| accessdate = 17 August 2007\n}}{{Dead link|date=April 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n</ref> He suffered a muscle strain in his upper thigh after a [[Exhibition game|friendly]] for [[Egypt national football team|Egypt]], and was ruled out of Ajax's game against Groningen.<ref name=\"Latest: Injured Mido won't Play Against Groningen\">\n{{Cite news\n| title = Latest: Injured Mido won't Play Against Groningen\n| url = http://egyptianplayers.com/archive/mido/articles-mido-15-2-2003.htm\n| publisher = Egyptian Players\n| date = 15 February 2003\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012\n}}{{Dead link|date=April 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n</ref> Mido was relegated to the Ajax [[reserve team]] for disciplinary reasons,<ref name=\"Ajax sanction Mido\">{{cite news\n| title = Ajax sanction Mido\n| url = http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/africa/2787341.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 21 February 2003\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012}}</ref> surrounding a perceived lack of effort in training.<ref name=\"Update on Mido's Case\">\n{{cite news\n| title = Update on Mido's Case\n| url = http://egyptianplayers.com/archive/mido/articles-mido-23-2-2003.htm\n| publisher = Egyptian Players\n| date = 23 February 2003\n| accessdate = 17 August 2007\n}}{{Dead link|date=April 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n</ref> His situation at the club led to interest from [[Serie A]] clubs [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]] and [[S.S. Lazio|Lazio]] and he later admitted to have thrown a pair of scissors at Ajax teammate [[Zlatan Ibrahimovi\u0107]] following an argument in March 2003.<ref name=\"Juventus eye Mido\">{{Cite news\n| title = Juventus eye Mido\n| url = http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/africa/2199945.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 17 August 2002\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Mido told to mend his ways\">{{Cite news\n| first = Gerrit\n| last = van Leeuwen\n| title = Mido told to mend his ways\n| url = http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11862_2258431,00.html\n| publisher = Sky Sports\n| date = 21 February 2003\n| accessdate = 29 June 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"More of the Mido case revealed\">\n{{cite news\n| title = More of the Mido case revealed\n| url = http://egyptianplayers.com/archive/mido/articles-mido-7-3-2003.htm\n| publisher = Egyptian Players\n| date = 7 March 2003\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012\n}}{{Dead link|date=April 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n</ref>\n\n====Loan to Celta Vigo====\n[[Celta de Vigo|Celta Vigo]] made a [[Loan (sports)|loan]] offer for Mido in March,<ref name=\"Celta hint at Mido offer\">{{Cite news\n| first = Alex\n| last = Levie\n| title = Celta hint at Mido offer\n| url = http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11849_2265763,00.html\n| publisher = Sky Sports\n| accessdate = 29 March 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Mido moves to Celta Vigo\">{{Cite news\n| first = Amr\n| last = Shaheen\n| title = Mido moves to Celta Vigo\n| url = http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/africa/2834201.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 9 March 2003\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012}}</ref> which was reported to have fallen through days later as it was not approved by [[FIFA]].<ref name=\"Mido move scuppered\">{{Cite news\n| title = Mido move scuppered\n| url = http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/africa/2848105.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 13 March 2003\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012}}</ref> However, FIFA eventually allowed the move to go through and it was completed on 18 March.<ref name=\"Fifa sanctions Mido loan\">{{cite news\n| title = Fifa sanctions Mido loan\n| url = http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/africa/2853385.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 16 March 2003\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Mido Presented\">\n{{Cite news\n| title = Mido Presented\n| url = http://egyptianplayers.com/archive/mido/articles-mido-21-3-2003.htm\n| publisher = Egyptian Players\n| date = 18 March 2003\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012\n}}{{Dead link|date=April 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n</ref> He scored on his Celta Vigo debut against [[Athletic Bilbao]], which Celta won 2\u20131.<ref name=\"Mido scores on Celta debut\">{{Cite news\n| title = Mido scores on Celta debut\n| url = http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/africa/2881193.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 24 March 2003\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012 }}</ref> Ajax valued Mido between the values of \u20ac5&nbsp;million and \u20ac6&nbsp;million, amidst interest from clubs in Italy and Spain.<ref name=\"Ajax want \u20ac5 million for Mido!\">\n{{cite news\n| title = Ajax want \u20ac5 million for Mido!\n| url = http://egyptianplayers.com/archive/mido/articles-mido-17-4-2003.htm\n| publisher = Egyptian Players\n| date = 16 April 2003\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012\n}}{{Dead link|date=April 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n</ref> [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] were reportedly on the verge of making a bid for Mido in May, but this was ruled out by Mido's agent Christophe Henrotay.<ref name=\"Magpies unlikely to move for Mido\">{{Cite news\n| first = Alex\n| last = Levie\n| title = Magpies unlikely to move for Mido\n| url = http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11678/2264831/\n| publisher = Sky Sports\n| date = 6 May 2003\n| accessdate = 29 June 2012}}</ref> Ajax attempted to make him return to the club, but he declined this, in favour of staying at Celta.<ref name=\"No\">\n{{cite news\n| title = Mido will say \"No\" to Koeman\n| url = http://egyptianplayers.com/archive/mido/articles-mido-15-5-2003.htm\n| publisher = Egyptian Players\n| date = 15 May 2003\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012\n}}{{Dead link|date=April 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n</ref> He suffered a muscle injury whilst training in May,<ref name=\"Mido injured again!\">\n{{cite news\n| title = Mido injured again!\n| url = http://egyptianplayers.com/archive/mido/articles-mido-16-5-2003.htm\n| publisher = Egyptian Players\n| date = 16 May 2003\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012\n}}{{Dead link|date=April 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n</ref> but was available to play in Celta's match against [[Villarreal CF]], which saw Mido sent off in a game which Celta lost 5\u20130.<ref name=\"Villarreal 5\u20130 Celta Vigo \u2013 Celta Vigo official website\">{{Cite news\n| title = Villarreal 5\u20130 Celta Vigo\n| url = http://www.celtavigo.net/sections.php?op=viewarticle&artid=263\n| publisher = Celta Vigo\n| date = 18 May 2003\n| accessdate = 29 June 2012\n| language = Spanish\n| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20050305072225/http://www.celtavigo.net/sections.php?op=viewarticle&artid=263\n| archivedate = 5 March 2005}}</ref><ref name=\"Villarreal 5\u20130 Celta Vigo \u2013 ESPN\">{{Cite news\n| title = Villarreal 5\u20130 Celta Vigo\n| url = http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=65727&cc=5739\n| publisher = ESPN Soccernet\n| date = 18 May 2003\n| accessdate = 29 June 2012}}</ref> Mido was linked with a move to [[A.S. Roma]] in late May, with Roma chairman Franco Sensi stating \"I want Mido\",<ref name=\"Sensi Pledges for Mido Capture\">\n{{cite news\n| title = Sensi Pledges for Mido Capture\n| url = http://egyptianplayers.com/archive/mido/articles-mido-30-5-2003.htm\n| publisher = Egyptian Players\n| date = 30 May 2003\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012\n}}{{Dead link|date=April 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n</ref> but Ajax revealed they wanted \u20ac15&nbsp;million for him.<ref name=\"Ajax want 15 Million EUROs for Mido!\">\n{{cite news\n| title = Ajax want 15 Million EUROs for Mido!\n| url = http://egyptianplayers.com/archive/mido/articles-mido-11-6-2003.htm\n| publisher = Egyptian Players\n| date = 11 June 2003\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012\n}}{{Dead link|date=April 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n</ref> Ajax turned down a loan move from [[Real Betis]] for Mido in June.<ref name=\"Ajax turn down Betis approach\">{{Cite news\n| first = Gerrit\n| last = van Leeuwen\n| title = Ajax turn down Betis approach\n| url = http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11847_2267862,00.html\n| publisher = Sky Sports\n| accessdate = 29 June 2012}}</ref> [[Olympique de Marseille|Marseille]] were then believed to have made an offer for the striker and Celta were not ready to meet Ajax's asking price of \u20ac15&nbsp;million.<ref name=\"Mido talks with Marseille\">{{Cite news\n| first = Amr\n| last = Shaheen\n| title = Mido talks with Marseille\n| url = http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/africa/3028788.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 28 June 2003\n| accessdate = 29 June 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Gomez\">\n{{Cite news\n| title = Gomez: \"We can't spend 15 M EUROs for Mido\"\n| url = http://egyptianplayers.com/archive/mido/articles-mido-22-6-2003.htm\n| publisher = Egyptian Players\n| date = 22 June 2003\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012\n}}{{Dead link|date=April 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n</ref>\n\n===Marseille===\nAjax accepted a \u20ac12&nbsp;million bid for Mido from Marseille in July,<ref name=\"Mido talks with Marseille\"/> and completed the move on a five-year contract on 12 July 2003,<ref name=\"Mido seals Marseille move\">{{cite news\n| title = Mido seals Marseille move\n| first = Amr\n| last = Shaheen\n| url = http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/africa/3395697.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 13 July 2003\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012}}</ref> which made Mido the most expensive Egyptian player ever.<ref name=\"Mido carries Egypt's hopes\">{{cite news\n| title = Mido carries Egypt's hopes\n| url = http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/africa/3395697.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 16 January 2004\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012}}</ref> He made his debut for Marseille in 1\u20130 win over [[En Avant de Guingamp|Guingamp]] on 1 August 2003.<ref name=\"Flurry of goals in France\">{{cite news\n| title = Flurry of goals in France\n| url = http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/africa/3130125.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 6 August 2003\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012}}</ref> [[Jean-Pierre Papin]] gave praise to Mido, saying it was down to players like him that the French [[Ligue 1]] was among the top European leagues.<ref name=\"Mido praised by Papin\">\n{{cite news\n| title = Mido praised by Papin\n| url = http://egyptianplayers.com/archive/mido/articles-mido-11-9-2003.htm\n| publisher = Egyptian Players\n| date = 11 September 2003\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012\n}}{{Dead link|date=April 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n</ref> He scored against [[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]] in a [[UEFA Champions League]] match in November, which Marseille lost 2\u20131.<ref name=\"Marseille 1\u20132 Real Madrid: Becks\">{{Cite news\n| title = Marseille 1\u20132 Real Madrid: Becks\n| url = http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=131411&cc=5739\n| publisher = ESPN Soccernet\n| date = 26 November 2003\n| accessdate = 29 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nMido stated in March 2004 that he may leave Marseille at the end of the 2003\u201304 season.<ref name=\"Mido seeking l'OM exit\">{{Cite news\n| first = Patrick\n| last = Haond\n| title = Mido seeking l'OM exit\n| url = http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11810/2296222/\n| publisher = Sky Sports\n| date = 13 April 2004\n| accessdate = 29 June 2012 }}</ref> An English club and several Spanish clubs were believed to be interested in signing Mido, who had been overshadowed at Marseille by [[Didier Drogba]].<ref name=\"Henrotay Confirms English and Spanish Interest\">\n{{cite news\n| title = Henrotay Confirms English and Spanish Interest\n| url = http://egyptianplayers.com/archive/NewMido/articles-mido77.htm\n| publisher = Egyptian Players\n| date = 27 April 2004\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012\n}}{{Dead link|date=April 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n</ref> [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]], [[Real Zaragoza|Zaragoza]], [[CA Osasuna|Osasuna]] and former club Celta Vigo were all rumoured to be interested in signing Mido, with Atl\u00e9tico's interest being confirmed by their Technical Director Toni Mu\u00f1oz.<ref name=\"Atletico attracted by Mido\">{{Cite news\n| first = Francisco\n| last = Acedo\n| title = Atletico attracted by Mido\n| url = http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11810/2297715/\n| publisher = Sky Sports\n| date = 28 April 2004\n| accessdate = 29 June 2012}}</ref> Meanwhile, Mido was caught speeding on the way to Marseille's game against [[AS Monaco FC|AS Monaco]], which resulted in a court hearing.<ref name=\"Mido caught speeding!\">\n{{Cite news\n| title = Mido caught speeding!\n| url = http://egyptianplayers.com/archive/NewMido/articles-mido91.htm\n| publisher = Egyptian Players\n| date = 11 May 2004\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012\n}}{{Dead link|date=April 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n</ref> Reports suggested Roma were ready to sign Mido for a fee of \u20ac9&nbsp;million even though Mido would be out injured for the rest of the French football season.<ref name=\"Mido on the road to Rome?\">\n{{Cite news\n| title = Mido on the road to Rome?\n| url = http://egyptianplayers.com/archive/NewMido/articles-mido93.htm\n| publisher = Egyptian Players\n| date = 13 May 2004\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012\n}}{{Dead link|date=April 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n</ref><ref name=\"Mido out until end of season\">\n{{cite news\n| title = Mido out until end of season\n| url = http://egyptianplayers.com/archive/NewMido/articles-mido94.htm\n| publisher = Egyptian Players\n| date = 14 May 2004\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012\n}}{{Dead link|date=April 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n</ref> Turkish side [[Be\u015fikta\u015f J.K.|Be\u015fikta\u015f]] revealed they wanted to sign him, and Mido said he was to have talks with [[Bobby Robson]] about a possible move to [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]].<ref name=\"Besiktas keen on Mido!\">\n{{cite news\n| title = Besiktas keen on Mido!\n| url = http://egyptianplayers.com/archive/NewMido/articles-mido99.htm\n| publisher = Egyptian Players\n| date = 20 May 2004\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012\n}}{{Dead link|date=April 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n</ref><ref name=\"Newcastle 2\">\n{{cite news\n| title = Mido: \"I am in talks with Newcastle\"\n| url = http://egyptianplayers.com/archive/NewMido/articles-mido101.htm\n| publisher = Egyptian Players\n| date = 25 May 2004\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012\n}}{{Dead link|date=April 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n</ref>\n\n===Roma===\nMido eventually signed for Roma on the final day of the 2004 summer transfer window, for a fee of \u20ac6&nbsp;million, signing a five-year contract.<ref name=\"Roma move for Mido\">{{Cite news\n| title = Roma move for Mido\n| url = http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=221041.html\n| publisher = UEFA\n| date = 31 August 2004\n| accessdate = 29 June 2012}}</ref> It was confirmed that he would miss the opening game of the season, and possibly the following two games.<ref name=\"Mido to miss season opener!\">\n{{cite news\n| title = Mido to miss season opener!\n| url = http://egyptianplayers.com/archive/NewMido/articles-mido189.htm\n| publisher = Egyptian Players\n| date = 8 September 2004\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012\n}}{{Dead link|date=April 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n</ref> Mido was penciled in to make his Roma debut against [[A.C.R. Messina|Messina]] in September 2004, a game in which he did actually play, but Roma lost 4\u20133.<ref name=\"Mido likely to Play\">\n{{cite news\n| title = Mido likely to Play\n| url = http://egyptianplayers.com/archive/NewMido/articles-mido197.htm\n| publisher = Egyptian Players\n| date = 19 September 2004\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012\n}}{{Dead link|date=April 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n</ref><ref name=\"Mido played in Roma loss!\">\n{{cite news\n| title = Mido played in Roma loss!\n| url = http://egyptianplayers.com/archive/NewMido/articles-mido198.htm\n| publisher = Egyptian Players\n| date = 19 September 2004\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012\n}}{{Dead link|date=April 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n</ref> Reports suggested that Mido could be sold to [[Valencia CF|Valencia]] in a swap deal with [[Bernardo Corradi]] and was also linked with a move to [[Premier League]] side [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]].<ref name=\"Roma offer Mido to Valencia!\">\n{{cite news\n| title = Roma offer Mido to Valencia!\n| url = http://egyptianplayers.com/archive/NewMido/articles-mido221.htm\n| publisher = Egyptian Players\n| date = 6 November 2004\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012\n}}{{Dead link|date=April 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n</ref><ref name=\"Mido to leave in January?\">\n{{cite news\n| title = Mido to leave in January?\n| url = http://egyptianplayers.com/archive/NewMido/articles-mido224.htm\n| publisher = Egyptian Players\n| date = 14 November 2004\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012\n}}{{Dead link|date=April 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n</ref> [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] were believed to have had Mido on their shortlist of targets, but his agent Christophe Henrotay said Roma would not be willing to let Mido leave the club.<ref name=\"Southampton in for Mido!\">\n{{cite news\n| title = Southampton in for Mido!\n| url = http://egyptianplayers.com/archive/NewMido/articles-mido241.htm\n| publisher = Egyptian Players\n| date = 22 December 2004\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012\n}}{{Dead link|date=April 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n</ref><ref name=\"Mido's Agent\">\n{{cite news\n| title = Mido's Agent: \"Roma not prepared to let him go\"\n| url = http://egyptianplayers.com/archive/NewMido/articles-mido242.htm\n| publisher = Egyptian Players\n| date = 22 December 2004\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012\n}}{{Dead link|date=April 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n</ref> It was even reported that he had been offered to Southampton on loan but his new agent, [[Mino Raiola]], repeated the earlier claims that Roma wanted to keep Mido until, at least, the end of the season.<ref name=\"Roma offer Mido to Saints\">\n{{cite news\n| title = Roma offer Mido to Saints\n| url = http://egyptianplayers.com/archive/NewMido/articles-mido250.htm\n| publisher = Egyptian Players\n| date = 13 January 2005\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012\n}}{{Dead link|date=April 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n</ref><ref name=\"Mido likely to remain at Roma\">\n{{cite news\n| title = Mido likely to remain at Roma\n| url = http://egyptianplayers.com/archive/NewMido/articles-mido251.htm\n| publisher = Egyptian Players\n| date = 16 January 2005\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012\n}}{{Dead link|date=April 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n</ref> He was linked with a move to [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]], with his agent confirming he wanted a move away from Roma.<ref name=\"Agent Plays Down Tottenham Talks!\">\n{{cite news\n| title = Agent Plays Down Tottenham Talks!\n| url = http://egyptianplayers.com/archive/NewMido/articles-mido255.htm\n| publisher = Egyptian Players\n| date = 19 January 2005\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012\n}}{{Dead link|date=April 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n</ref>\n\n===Tottenham Hotspur===\n[[File:Mido 11.JPG|150px|thumb|Mido playing for [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] in 2007]]\nMido was signed by Tottenham on an 18-month loan deal on 28 January 2005.<ref name=\"Mido completes Tottenham switch\">{{cite news\n| title = Mido completes Tottenham switch\n| url = http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=323242&cc=5739\n| publisher = ESPNsoccernet\n| date = 28 January 2005\n| accessdate = 11 November 2007}}</ref> He scored two goals on his Tottenham debut against [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]] on 5 February 2005.<ref name=\"Tottenham 3-1 Portsmouth\">{{cite news\n| title = Tottenham 3\u20131 Portsmouth\n| url = http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/4218249.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 5 February 2005\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012}}</ref> He scored 3 goals in 11 appearances during the [[2004\u201305 in English football|2004\u201305]] season for Tottenham.<ref name=\"Games played by Ahmed Mido in 2004/2005\">{{Soccerbase season|26761|2004|name=Ahmed Mido|accessdate=29 June 2012}}</ref> Mido announced plans in July 2005 to launch his own football academy in Egypt, which had the aim of nurturing the country's young talent.<ref name=\"Mido launches football academy\">{{Cite news\n| first = Amr\n| last = Shaheen\n| title = Mido launches football academy\n| url = http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/africa/4660969.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 7 May 2005\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012}}</ref> In January 2006, he expressed that he did not wish to return to Roma at the end of the [[2005\u201306 in English football|2005\u201306]] season, but rather sign permanently with Tottenham.<ref name=\"Spurs' Mido rules out Roma return\">{{Cite news\n| title = Spurs' Mido rules out Roma return\n| url = http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/4603414.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 11 January 2006\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012}}</ref> Tottenham manager [[Martin Jol]] said that the club were confident of signing Mido on a permanent deal due to his good performances,<ref name=\"Egyptian Players Abroad\">\n{{Cite news\n| title = Egyptian Players Abroad: Player's Profile Ahmed Hossam (\"Mido\") \u2013 Tottenham Hotspur (England)\n| url = http://www.socceregypt.com/index.php/2006/05/05/ahmed_hossam_mido_tottenham_hotspur_engl\n| publisher = SoccerEgypt\n| date = 5 May 2006\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120722102045/http://www.socceregypt.com/index.php/2006/05/05/ahmed_hossam_mido_tottenham_hotspur_engl\n| archivedate = 22 July 2012\n| url-status = dead\n}}\n</ref> but later admitted Tottenham may be defeated in keeping Mido, with other clubs interested in signing him.<ref name=\"Jol faces a struggle to keep Mido\">{{cite news\n| title = Jol faces a struggle to keep Mido\n| url = http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/4858714.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 30 March 2006\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012}}</ref> His permanent move was further put into doubt in April 2006, after he suffered a new injury problem.<ref name=\"Mido's move to Spurs now in doubt\">{{cite news\n| title = Mido's move to Spurs now in doubt\n| url = http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/4947620.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 26 April 2006\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012}}</ref> He suffered abuse from a small section of the [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] and [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] fans in 2005. West Ham manager [[Alan Pardew]] apologised to Mido for the abuse by the fans.<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Saints to probe Mido abuse claims\n| url = http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/4334509.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 9 March 2005\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| title = Pardew apologises for Mido abuse\n| url = http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/4465580.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 24 November 2005\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012}}</ref> He finished the [[2005\u201306 in English football|2005\u201306]] season with 11 goals in 27 games, meaning he was Tottenham's second highest goalscorer.<ref name=\"Games played by Ahmed Mido in 2005/2006\">{{Soccerbase season|26761|2005|name=Ahmed Mido|accessdate=17 September 2012}}</ref> Tottenham confirmed in May 2006 that Mido would be returning to Roma.<ref name=\"Tottenham part company with Mido\">{{cite news\n| title = Tottenham part company with Mido\n| url = http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/5021836.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 26 May 2006\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012}}</ref>\n\nHowever, Mido re-joined Tottenham on 29 August on a permanent deal for a fee of \u20ac6.75&nbsp;million.<ref name=\"A titolo definito del diritto alle prestazioni sportive\">{{Cite news\n| title = A titolo definito del diritto alle prestazioni sportive\n| url = http://www.asroma.it/UserFiles/595.pdf\n| publisher = A.S. Roma\n| format = PDF\n| date = 29 August 2006\n| accessdate = 8 March 2010\n| language = Italian\n}}</ref><ref name=\"Tottenham agree deal to sign Mido\">{{cite news\n| title = Tottenham agree deal to sign Mido\n| url = http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/5294226.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 29 August 2006\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012}}</ref> After returning to Tottenham he commented on the team's official website that he \"always knew in his heart he would be coming back\" and that he \"couldn't wait to pull on a Tottenham shirt, play at the Lane and score some more goals\".<ref name=\"Mido returns\">{{Cite news\n| title = Mido returns\n| url = http://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/articles/midoreturns290806.html\n| publisher = Tottenham Hotspur F.C\n| date = 29 August 2006\n| accessdate = 17 August 2007\n| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080724095537/http://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/articles/midoreturns290806.html\n| archivedate = 24 July 2008}}</ref> However, soon after this, Mido was accused of being \"irresponsible and disrespectful\" by his manager Martin Jol, following comments Mido had made about former Tottenham player [[Sol Campbell]].<ref name=\"Jol infuriated by outspoken Mido\">{{Cite news\n| title = Jol infuriated by outspoken Mido\n| url = http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/5395580.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 30 August 2006\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012}}</ref> After failing to score in his first five appearances as a permanent Tottenham player, he finally found the net against rivals West Ham with a match-winning volley on 19 October 2006,<ref name=\"Tottenham 1-0 West Ham\">{{Cite news\n| first = Ian\n| last = Hughes\n| title = Tottenham 1\u20130 West Ham\n| url = http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/6050700.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 19 October 2006\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012}}</ref> and followed that with two goals against [[Football League Two|League Two]] side [[Milton Keynes Dons F.C.|Milton Keynes Dons]] in the [[Football League Cup|League Cup]].<ref name=\"MK Dons 0-5 Tottenham\">{{cite news\n| title = MK Dons 0\u20135 Tottenham\n| url = http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/league_cup/6072616.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 25 October 2006\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012}}</ref> He had to contend with being fourth in line for one of the two striking spots, but insisted that this was a sign of the club's strength, and something he was fully aware of before rejoining the club.<ref>{{Cite web\n| title = Svelte Spurs striker Mido drops 22&nbsp;lb\n| publisher = ESPN Soccernet\n| url = http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=378266&cc=5739\n| accessdate = 1 December 2006}}</ref> However, he was linked with a move to Manchester City.<ref name=\"Man City considering Mido swoop\">{{cite news\n| title = Man City considering Mido swoop\n| url = http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/6295807.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 24 January 2007\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012}}</ref> Mido scored what looked to be his final goal for Tottenham on 31 January 2007 against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]], but his potential move to Manchester City fell through half an hour before the close of the transfer window.<ref name=\"Arsenal 3-1 Tottenham (agg 5-3)\">{{Cite news\n| first = Sam\n| last = Lyon\n| title = Arsenal 3\u20131 Tottenham (agg 5\u20133)\n| url = http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/league_cup/6305313.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 30 January 2007\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Pearce stunned over Mido U-turn\">{{cite news\n| title = Pearce stunned over Mido U-turn\n| url = http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/6321915.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 1 February 2007\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012}}</ref> He eventually admitted he made a mistake by joining Tottenham on a permanent deal.<ref name=\"Spurs deal was big mistake - Mido\">{{cite news\n| title = Spurs deal was big mistake \u2013 Mido\n| url = http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/6678251.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 21 May 2007\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012}}</ref> He ended the [[2006\u201307 in English football|2006\u201307]] season with 23 appearances and 5 goals.<ref name=\"Games played by Ahmed Mido in 2006/2007\">{{Soccerbase season|26761|2006|name=Ahmed Mido|accessdate=17 September 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Middlesbrough===\nTottenham agreed a \u00a36&nbsp;million fee with [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] for Mido on 20 July 2007.<ref name=\"Birmingham agree \u00a36m fee for Mido\">{{cite news\n| title = Birmingham agree \u00a36m fee for Mido\n| url = http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/6904038.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 20 July 2007\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012}}</ref> Birmingham manager [[Steve Bruce]] said the move was close to collapsing, as the deal reportedly faltered over the wages and the length of contract Mido was demanding.<ref name=\"Mido's Blues deal in danger\">{{cite news\n| title = Mido's Blues deal in danger\n| url = https://www.fifa.com/worldfootball/clubfootball/news/newsid=559739.html\n| publisher = FIFA\n| date = 26 July 2007\n| accessdate = 18 August 2007}}</ref> The deal eventually fell through over a clause that Mido insisted be in the contract.<ref name=\"Sunderland confirm offer for Mido\">{{cite news\n| title = Sunderland confirm offer for Mido\n| url = http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/6932892.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 6 August 2007\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012}}</ref> In August 2007 [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] made a \u00a36&nbsp;million bid for him and held talks,<ref name=\"Sunderland confirm offer for Mido\"/> after which Birmingham confirmed they were trying to revive their deal to sign Mido.<ref name=\"Birmingham revive Mido interest\">{{cite news\n| title = Birmingham revive Mido interest\n| url = http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/6937785.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 8 August 2007\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012}}</ref> [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]] then revealed their interest in signing him, matching the \u00a36&nbsp;million fee of Birmingham and Sunderland and were given permission to speak to him.<ref name=\"Middlesbrough enter race for Mido\">{{cite news\n| title = Middlesbrough enter race for Mido\n| url = http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/6939590.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 9 August 2007\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012}}</ref> They eventually signed Mido for a fee of \u00a36&nbsp;million on a four-year contract on 16 August 2007.<ref name=\"Middlesbrough finalise Mido move\">{{Cite news\n| title = Middlesbrough finalise Mido move\n| url = http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/6950238.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 16 August 2007\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012}}</ref> He scored on his debut for Middlesbrough against [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] and on his home debut against [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]].<ref name=\"Fulham 1-2 Middlesbrough\">{{Cite news\n| first = John\n| last = May\n| title = Fulham 1\u20132 Middlesbrough\n| url = http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/6941857.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 18 August 2007\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Middlesbrough 2-2 Newcastle\">{{Cite news\n| first = Julian\n| last = Shea\n| title = Middlesbrough 2\u20132 Newcastle\n| url = http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/6952886.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 26 August 2007\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012}}</ref> During the Newcastle game, Mido was reportedly subject to [[Islamophobia|Islamophobic]] abuse from some Newcastle supporters, which [[The Football Association]] (The FA) was to investigate.<ref name=\"FA to investigate Mido racist chants\">{{Cite news\n| first = Rob\n| last = Stewart\n| title = FA to investigate Mido racist chants\n| url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/main.jhtml?view=DETAILS&grid=A1YourView&xml=/sport/2007/08/29/sfnmid129.xml\n| newspaper = The Daily Telegraph\n| location = London\n| date = 29 August 2007\n| accessdate = 25 September 2007\n| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110604182803/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/2320057/FA-to-investigate-Mido-racist-chants.html\n| archivedate = 4 June 2011}}</ref>\n\nHe suffered a stress fracture to the pubic bone which kept him out for more than three months from November 2007 until he returned to first-team action for Middlesbrough's 2\u20130 [[FA Cup]] victory over [[Mansfield Town F.C.|Mansfield Town]] on 26 January 2008.<ref>{{Cite news\n| first = Paul\n| last = Fraser\n| title = Mido's return could prove a headache for Southgate\n| url = http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/sport/football/middlesbrough/news/1948708.Mido___s_return_could_prove_a_headache_for_Southgate/\n| newspaper = The Northern Echo\n| location = Darlington\n| date = 8 January 2008\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news\n| first = Scott\n| last = Wilson\n| title = Boro content to look ahead after progress\n| url = http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/sport/football/middlesbrough/reports/1998412.Boro_content_to_look_ahead_after_progress/\n| newspaper = The Northern Echo\n| location = Darlington\n| date = 28 January 2008\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012}}</ref> He was sent off in the 80th minute in a match against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] on 15 March 2008 after kicking [[Ga\u00ebl Clichy]] in the face with his boot,<ref name=\"Arsenal 1-1 Middlesbrough\">{{cite news\n| first = Saj\n| last = Chowdhury\n| title = Arsenal 1\u20131 Middlesbrough\n| url = http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/7284973.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 15 March 2008\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012}}</ref> which resulted in him receiving a three-match ban.<ref name=\"Mido will serve three-match ban\">{{cite news\n| title = Mido will serve three-match ban\n| url = http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/7302296.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 18 March 2008\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012}}</ref> Mido was ruled out for the remainder of the [[2007\u201308 in English football|2007\u201308]] season in April following a [[hernia]] operation on a pelvic injury.<ref name=\"Mido to miss rest of the season\">{{cite news\n| title = Mido to miss rest of the season\n| url = http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/7328996.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 3 April 2008\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012}}</ref> He made the bench for Middlesbrough's opening Premier League fixture against former club Tottenham and came on as a substitute in the 82nd minute and scored four minutes later after deflecting [[Didier Digard]]'s shot.<ref name=\"Middlesbrough 2-1 Tottenham\">{{cite news\n| first = Sam\n| last = Lyon\n| title = Middlesbrough 2\u20131 Tottenham\n| url = http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/7551168.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 16 August 2008\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012}}</ref> The following weekend saw him score against [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] at [[Anfield]] to put Middlesbrough 1\u20130 in the lead, but they eventually lost the game 2\u20131.<ref name=\"Liverpool 2-1 Middlesbrough\">{{cite news\n| first = Ian\n| last = Hughes\n| title = Liverpool 2\u20131 Middlesbrough\n| url = http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/7565060.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 23 August 2008\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012}}</ref> This was followed up with goals against [[Yeovil Town F.C.|Yeovil Town]] in the [[Football League Cup|League Cup]] and [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]] in the league.<ref name=\"Middlesbrough 5-1 Yeovil\">{{cite news\n| title = Middlesbrough 5\u20131 Yeovil\n| url = http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/league_cup/7576396.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 26 August 2008\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Portsmouth 2-1 Middlesbrough\">{{cite news\n| title = Portsmouth 2\u20131 Middlesbrough\n| url = http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/7601897.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 13 September 2008\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012}}</ref> Mido was again targeted by some Newcastle fans while warming up before Middlesbrough's 0\u20130 draw, with claims of racist chanting being investigated by The FA.<ref name=\"Briefs3-FA investigating claims of racist chanting against Mido\">{{Cite news\n| title = Briefs3-FA investigating claims of racist chanting against Mido\n| url = http://uk.reuters.com/article/2008/12/01/sport-briefs-idUKL137257820081201\n| agency = Reuters\n| date = 1 December 2008\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012}}</ref> He revealed his anger at The FA's investigation, believing that they would make no difference to any future abuse.<ref name=\"Mido fury at FA over repeat of racist taunts at Tyne-Tees clash\">{{Cite news\n| first = Simon\n| last = Williams\n| title = Mido fury at FA over repeat of racist taunts at Tyne-Tees clash\n| url = https://www.theguardian.com/football/2008/dec/04/middlesbrough-premierleague\n| newspaper = The Guardian\n| date = 4 December 2008\n| accessdate = 5 December 2008\n| location=London}}</ref> Two men were eventually arrested over the chanting and were due to appear at Teesside Magistrates Court.<ref name=\"Two arrested over Mido chanting\">{{Cite news\n| title = Two arrested over Mido chanting\n| url = http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/7758089.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 5 December 2008\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012}}</ref>\n\n====Loan to Wigan Athletic====\nMido entered talks with [[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]] over signing on a six-month loan deal,<ref name=\"Wigan's King makes Boro loan move\">{{Cite news\n| title = Wigan's King makes Boro loan move\n| url = http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/7845049.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 22 January 2009\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012}}</ref> and he completed the move on 23 January 2009.<ref name=\"Wigan sign striker Mido on loan\">{{cite news\n| title = Wigan sign striker Mido on loan\n| url = http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/7847669.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 23 January 2009\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012}}</ref> He scored on his debut with the equalizing goal against [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] with a penalty kick in a 1\u20131 draw on 28 January.<ref name=\"Wigan 1-1 Liverpool\">{{cite news\n| first = Paul\n| last = Fletcher\n| title = Wigan 1\u20131 Liverpool\n| url = http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/7844586.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 28 January 2009\n| accessdate = 28 January 2009}}</ref> He scored for Wigan in a 4\u20131 defeat against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] and he finished the loan spell with 12 appearances and 2 goals.<ref name=\"Games played by Ahmed Mido in 2008/2009\">{{Soccerbase season|26761|2008|name=Ahmed Mido|accessdate=17 September 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Wigan 1-4 Arsenal\">{{cite news\n| first = Mark\n| last = Ashenden\n| title = Wigan 1\u20134 Arsenal\n| url = http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/7978865.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 11 April 2009\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012}}</ref> Following Middlesbrough's [[promotion and relegation|relegation]] to the [[Football League Championship|Championship]], he failed to report to pre-season training,<ref name=\"Alves back as Mido remains absent\">{{cite news\n| title = Alves back as Mido remains absent\n| url = http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/8137881.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 8 July 2009\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012}}</ref> and he was eventually fined by the club after not turning up after a fortnight.<ref name=\"Mido back in training with Boro\">{{Cite news\n| title = Mido back in training with Boro\n| url = http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/africa/8159150.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 21 July 2009\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012}}</ref> He returned to training a day after this.<ref name=\"Mido back in training with Boro\"/>\n\n====Loan to Zamalek====\nMiddlesbrough accepted an undisclosed offer for Mido from an unnamed club on 26 July, and he completed a season-long move to former club Zamalek on 3 August,<ref name=\"Mido completes move back to Egypt\">{{Cite news\n| title = Mido completes move back to Egypt\n| url = http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/8169292.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 4 August 2009\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012}}</ref> who had an option to sign him permanently if they were able to meet Middlesbrough's terms.<ref name=\"Mido makes Zamalek move\">{{Cite news\n| title = Mido makes Zamalek move\n| url = http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11688_5463719,00.html\n| publisher = Sky Sports\n| date = 31 July 2009\n| accessdate = 20 July 2009}}</ref> On 20 August, Mido made a disappointing debut for Zamalek, wasting a second-half penalty as Zamalek threw away their lead to suffer a late 2\u20131 home victory to [[Petrojet]] in the [[Egyptian Premier League]].<ref name=\"Zamalek pay for Mido's wasted penalty\">{{Cite news\n| title = Zamalek pay for Mido's wasted penalty\n| first = Hatem\n| last = Maher\n| url = http://new.filgoal.com/English/News.aspx?NewsID=58748\n| publisher = Filgoal\n| date = 20 August 2009\n| accessdate = 22 August 2009}}</ref>\n\n====Loan to West Ham United====\n[[File:Mido 1.png|thumb|100px|Mido playing for [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] in 2010]]\nMido joined West Ham United on a four-month loan on 1 February 2010 after his season-long loan spell with Zamalek was terminated by mutual agreement.<ref name=\"Mido & Ilan join West Ham on loan\">{{Cite news\n| title = Mido & Ilan join West Ham on loan\n| url = http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/8492106.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 1 February 2010\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012}}</ref> He stated \"I had to sacrifice some things but I'm here to play football again and I'm here to prove a point. I'm very happy to be here, it's a great club \u2013 and I'm sure I'll do well here.\"<ref name=\"Mido & Ilan join West Ham on loan\"/> West Ham chairman [[David Sullivan (publisher)|David Sullivan]] announced that in order for Mido to secure his long-term footballing future, his contract with West Ham put him amongst the lowest earners in the Premier League.<ref name=\"Mido to be paid just \u00a31,000 per week as he bids to lift West Ham\">{{cite news\n| title = Mido to be paid just \u00a31,000 per week as he bids to lift West Ham\n| url = https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/mido-to-be-paid-just-1000-per-week-as-he-bids-to-lift-west-ham-6771136.html\n| newspaper = London Evening Standard\n| date = 2 February 2010\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012}}</ref> Sullivan said \"He doesn't want to be known as a 'has been' of English football, so he was willing to come here to play for a nominal fee, just \u00a31,000 a week.\"<ref name=\"Mido to be paid just \u00a31,000 per week as he bids to lift West Ham\"/> He made his debut for West Ham on 6 February in 2\u20131 away defeat against [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]].<ref>{{Cite news\n| title = Burnley 2\u20131 West Ham\n| url = http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/8497953.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 6 February 2010\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012}}</ref> In nine appearances for West Ham he failed to score and had a tame penalty saved in a 2\u20132 away draw against [[Everton F.C.|Everton]].<ref name=\"Everton 2 \u2013 2 West Ham\">{{cite news\n| first = Phil\n| last = Dawkes\n| title = Everton 2\u20132 West Ham\n| url = http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/8597527.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 4 April 2010\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012}}</ref> In June 2010, West Ham decided not to offer him a new contract.<ref>{{cite news\n |title       = Manager announcement due\n |url         = http://www.whufc.com/articles/20100602/manager-announcement-due_2236884_2054050\n |publisher   = West Ham United F.C\n |date        = 2 June 2010\n |accessdate  = 2 June 2010\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20100605180354/http://www.whufc.com/articles/20100602/manager-announcement-due_2236884_2054050\n |archivedate = 5 June 2010\n}}</ref>\n\n====Loan to Ajax====\nAjax entered talks with Middlesbrough over signing Mido on a free transfer in July.<ref name=\"Ajax eye Mido return\">{{cite news\n| first1 = Graeme\n| last1 = Bailey\n| first2 = Gerrit\n| last2 = van Leeuwen\n| title = Ajax eye Mido return\n| url = http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11682_6280285,00.html\n| publisher = Sky Sports\n| date = 26 July 2010\n| accessdate = 26 July 2010}}</ref> On 1 September, he signed a one-year loan contract.<ref name=\"Middlesbrough striker Mido returns to Ajax\">{{cite news\n| title = Middlesbrough striker Mido returns to Ajax\n| url = http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/africa/8938049.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 1 September 2010\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012}}</ref>\nMido made his league debut on 16 October 2010, coming on as a substitute for [[Miralem Sulejmani]] in a 3\u20130 win against [[NAC Breda]].<ref name=\"Ajax beat Breda to take top spot, Twente up to second\">\n{{cite news\n| title = Ajax beat Breda to take top spot, Twente up to second\n| first = Theo\n| last = Ruizenaar\n| url = http://football.uk.reuters.com/leagues/eredivisie/news/2010/10/16/LDE69F0EG.php\n| agency = Reuters\n| date = 16 October 2010\n| accessdate = 21 January 2011\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120311104028/http://football.uk.reuters.com/leagues/eredivisie/news/2010/10/16/LDE69F0EG.php\n| archivedate = 11 March 2012\n| url-status = dead\n}}\n</ref> He scored his first goal on 11 November in a 3\u20130 win against [[BV Veendam|Veendam]] in the [[Dutch Cup]].<ref name=\"Ajax laat langs BV Veendam (3\u20130)\">{{cite news\n| title = Ajax laat langs BV Veendam (3\u20130)\n| url = http://www.bndestem.nl/sport/sportalgemeen/7608319/Ajax-laat-langs-BV-Veendam-30.ece\n| newspaper = BN/De Stem\n| language = Dutch\n| date = 11 November 2010\n| accessdate = 21 January 2011}}</ref> Despite scoring three goals in six appearances, his first-team football opportunities were limited, having been on the starting line-up only once. After [[Martin Jol]] resigned, Mido lost his place when new manager [[Frank de Boer]] was appointed on 6 December 2010. On 4 January 2011, he wrote Ajax a letter to cancel his contract.<ref>{{Cite news\n| first = Ibrahim\n| last = Sannie\n| title = Egypt's Mido leaves Ajax at his own request\n| url = http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/africa/9337212.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 4 January 2011\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Return to Zamalek===\nOn 21 January 2011, Mido rejoined Zamalek on a three-and-a half-year contract.<ref name=\"Egypt striker Mido ready to rejoin Cairo's Zamalek.\">{{cite news |title=Egypt striker Mido ready to rejoin Cairo's Zamalek |url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Egypt+striker+Mido+ready+to+rejoin+Cairo%27s+Zamalek.-a0247195399 |work=Daily News Egypt |date=21 January 2011 |accessdate=17 September 2012}}</ref> However, due to an error made by Zamalek management Mido was not registered in time to play with Zamalek thus sitting out the remainder of the season.<ref name=\"retires\" />\n\n===Barnsley===\nOn 16 June 2012, Mido agreed a deal with English [[Football League Championship|Championship]] side [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]], subject to a medical.<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Mido agrees Tykes deal\n| url = http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/12691/7817427/Mido-agrees-Tykes-deal\n| publisher = Sky Sports\n| date = 16 June 2012\n| accessdate = 16 June 2012}}</ref> His move was completed on 21 June 2012 when he signed a one-year contract with Barnsley.<ref>{{Cite news\n| title = Mido joins Championship side Barnsley\n| url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/18469793\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 21 June 2012\n| accessdate = 23 June 2012}}</ref> Mido made his league debut on 10 November 2012 as a substitute for [[Kelvin Etuhu]] in a 1\u20130 home defeat against [[Huddersfield Town F.C.|Huddersfield Town]].<ref>{{Cite news\n| title = Barnsley 0\u20131 Huddersfield\n| url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/20190122\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 10 November 2012\n| accessdate = 22 January 2013}}</ref> On 31 January 2013 he was released by mutual consent<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.barnsleyfc.co.uk/news/article/mido-leaves-oakwell-630423.aspx|title=Mido Leaves Oakwell|accessdate=16 July 2015}}</ref> along with defender [[Lee Collins (footballer born 1988)|Lee Collins]].\n\n== Retirement ==\nHis retirement from football was announced in June 2013.<ref name=\"retires\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/22857567 |title=Mido: Egyptian retires from football at the age of 30 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=11 June 2013 |accessdate=25 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nPrior to his retirement, Mido was named Honorary Life President of the Old Wykehamist Football Club,<ref name=\"Honorary President of Old Wykehamist Football Club\">{{cite web | url=https://owfc.secure-club.com/officials/default.aspx | title=Old Wykehamist Football Club \u2013 Club Officials | date=23 April 2013 | accessdate=7 July 2013}}</ref> a club for alumni of [[Winchester College]] and one of the founding member clubs of the [[Arthurian League]].\n\n== International career ==\nMido played 13 times for the [[Egypt national under-20 football team|Egypt youth]] team between 1999 and 2001.<ref name=\"Intstats\">{{cite news\n| title = Ahmed Hossam (Mido)\n| url = http://www.angelfire.com/ak/EgyptianSports/AhmedHossam.html#International%20Caps\n| publisher = Angelfire\n| date = 1 February 2010\n| accessdate = 2 February 2010}}</ref>\n\nHe has earned 51 [[Cap (sport)#Association football|cap]]s for [[Egypt national football team|Egypt]] and scored 20 goals.<ref name=\"Hossam, Ahmed 'Mido'\"/><ref name=\"2001 Matches - Africa\">{{Cite news\n| first = Barrie\n| last = Courtney\n| title = 2001 Matches \u2013 Africa\n| url = http://www.rsssf.com/intldetails/2001af.html\n| publisher = Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation\n| date = 2 February 2005\n| accessdate = 21 January 2010}}</ref> Mido scored on his international debut against the [[United Arab Emirates national football team|United Arab Emirates]], which Egypt won 2\u20131.<ref name=\"Egyptian Players Abroad\"/> Mido sent a fax to the Egypt team to tell them he was not available for international selection in May 2004, saying he was not psychologically fit to join the team.<ref name=\"Mido snubs Egypt\">{{Cite news\n| first = Amr\n| last = Shaheen\n| title = Mido snubs Egypt\n| url = http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/africa/3686189.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 5 May 2004\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012}}</ref> Mido was a part of the Egypt squad that played at the [[2004 African Cup of Nations]].<ref name=\"Mido carries Egypt's hopes\"/>\n\nEgypt manager [[Marco Tardelli]] dropped Mido in September 2004, after Mido claimed to be unavailable for the national team due to an injury, but played in a friendly match for [[A.S. Roma|Roma]] 24 hours later.<ref name=\"Tardelli is finished with Mido\">{{Cite news\n| first = Amr\n| last = Shaheen\n| title = Tardelli is finished with Mido\n| url = http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/africa/3631958.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 6 September 2004\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Pharaohs prepare for Libya\">{{Cite news\n| first = Amr\n| last = Shaheen\n| title = Pharaohs prepare for Libya\n| url = http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/africa/4366297.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 20 March 2005\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012}}</ref> A day later, Mido rejected accusations that he refused to play for his country.<ref name=\"Mido defends himself\">{{Cite news\n| first = Amr\n| last = Shaheen\n| title = Mido defends himself\n| url = http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/africa/3635464.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 7 September 2004\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012}}</ref> Also, the [[Egyptian Football Association]] announced that he would not play for the team again. However, Tardelli was sacked as Egypt coach and in January 2005 the Egyptian Football Association said they would consider bringing Mido back into the team if he were to apologise for his past behaviour.<ref name=\"Egyptian Players Abroad\"/> Mido flew to [[Cairo]] in February 2005 and made a public apology and the following month he was recalled by the national team.<ref name=\"Pharaohs prepare for Libya\"/><ref name=\"Mido makes third apology\">{{cite news\n| title = Mido makes third apology\n| url = http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/africa/4262139.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 13 February 2005\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012}}</ref> Mido withdrew from Egypt's [[2006 FIFA World Cup (qualification)|2006 World Cup qualifier]] against [[Cameroon national football team|Cameroon]], after sustaining a muscle tear while playing with [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]].<ref name=\"Egypt hit by Mido injury\">{{Cite news\n| first = Amr\n| last = Shaheen\n| title = Egypt hit by Mido injury\n| url = http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/africa/4309046.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 4 October 2005\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012}}</ref>\n\nMido was thrown out of the Egypt team during the [[2006 African Cup of Nations]] as a consequence of an argument with coach [[Hassan Shehata]] in the semi-final game against [[Senegal national football team|Senegal]], which started after Mido reacted badly to being substituted. His replacement [[Amr Zaki]] came on to score a header with his first touch, putting Egypt into the final.<ref name=\"Mido thrown out of Egyptian squad\">{{Cite news\n| first = Matthew\n| last = Kenyon\n| title = Mido thrown out of Egyptian squad\n| url = http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/africa/4692714.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 8 February 2006\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012}}</ref> A day later, Mido reconciled with Shehata, but was given a six-month suspension from playing with Egypt.<ref name=\"Mido reconciles with Egypt coach\">{{Cite news\n| title = Mido reconciles with Egypt coach\n| url = http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/africa/4698504.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 9 February 2006\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012}}</ref> Mido was eventually recalled by the side following his suspension, ready for the [[2008 African Cup of Nations (qualification)|2008 African Cup of Nations qualification]] which Egypt won.<ref name=\"Mido makes Egypt return\">{{Cite news\n| first = Amr\n| last = Shaheen\n| title = Mido makes Egypt return\n| url = http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/africa/5270836.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 21 August 2006\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012}}</ref> Mido was included in the Egypt squad to play [[South Africa national football team|South Africa]] in London in November 2006, despite suffering from a knee injury at the time.<ref name=\"Egypt call Mido despite injury\">{{Cite news\n| title = Egypt call Mido despite injury\n| url = http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/africa/6141796.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 12 November 2006\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012}}</ref> However, he was left out of the Egypt squad to play [[Mauritania national football team|Mauritania]] in an African Nations Cup qualifier in March 2007.<ref name=\"Mido out of Egypt squad\">{{cite news\n| title = Mido out of Egypt squad\n| url = http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/africa/6474461.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 31 March 2007\n| accessdate = 17 September 2012}}</ref>\n\n===International goals===\n:''Egypt score listed first, score column indicates score after each Mido goal.''<ref>{{cite web |first=Hazem |last=Adel |url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/mido-intlg.html |title=Ahmed Hossam Hussein \"Mido\" \u2013 Goals in international matches |publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation |date=6 January 2016 |accessdate=26 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\"\n|+ International goals by date, venue, opponent, score, result and competition\n|-\n!scope=\"col\"|No.\n!scope=\"col\" data-sort-type=\"date\"|Date\n!scope=\"col\"|Venue\n!scope=\"col\"|Cap\n!scope=\"col\"|Opponent\n!scope=\"col\"|Score\n!scope=\"col\"|Result\n!scope=\"col\"|Competition\n|-\n!scope=row|1\n|6 January 2001||rowspan=2|[[Cairo International Stadium]], [[Cairo]], Egypt||1||{{fb|United Arab Emirates}}||2\u20131||2\u20131||[[Exhibition game#Association football|Friendly]]\n|-\n!scope=row|2\n|6 May 2001||8||{{fb|Senegal}}||rowspan=2|1\u20130||1\u20130||[[2002 FIFA World Cup qualification (CAF)|2002 FIFA World Cup qualification]]\n|-\n!scope=row|3\n|rowspan=2|3 June 2001||rowspan=2|[[Alexandria Stadium]], [[Alexandria]], Egypt||rowspan=2|9||rowspan=2|{{fb|Sudan}}||rowspan=2|3\u20132||rowspan=2|[[2002 African Cup of Nations qualification]]\n|-\n!scope=row|4\n|2\u20130\n|-\n!scope=row|5\n|10 June 2001||[[Moi International Sports Centre]], [[Nairobi]], Kenya||10||{{fb|Kenya}}||rowspan=2|1\u20131||rowspan=2|1\u20131||Friendly\n|-\n!scope=row|6\n|21 July 2001||[[Stade 19 Mai 1956]], [[Annaba]], Algeria||13||{{fb|Algeria}}||2002 FIFA World Cup qualification\n|-\n!scope=row|7\n|30 December 2001||[[Khalifa International Stadium]], [[Doha]], Qatar||14||{{fb|Qatar}}||2\u20131||2\u20132||rowspan=3|Friendly\n|-\n!scope=row|8\n|6 January 2002||[[Ismailia Stadium]], [[Ismailia]], Egypt||16||{{fb|Mali}}||rowspan=5|1\u20130||1\u20132\n|-\n!scope=row|9\n|11 January 2002||Cairo International Stadium, Cairo, Egypt||17||{{fb|Burkina Faso}}||2\u20132\n|-\n!scope=row|10\n|31 January 2002||[[Stade Modibo K\u00e9\u00efta]], [[Bamako]], Mali||20||{{fb|Zambia}}||2\u20131||[[2002 African Cup of Nations]]\n|-\n!scope=row|11\n|29 March 2003||Rose Hill Stadium, [[Port Louis]], Mauritius||24||rowspan=3|{{fb|Mauritius}}||1\u20130||rowspan=4|[[2004 African Cup of Nations qualification]]\n|-\n!scope=row|12\n|rowspan=2|8 June 2003||rowspan=3|[[Port Said Stadium]], [[Port Said]], Egypt||rowspan=2|26||rowspan=2|7\u20130\n|-\n!scope=row|13\n|3\u20130\n|-\n!scope=row|14\n|20 June 2003||27||{{fb|Madagascar}}||4\u20130||6\u20130\n|-\n!scope=row|15\n|10 October 2003||rowspan=2|Cairo International Stadium, Cairo, Egypt||28||{{fb|Senegal}}||1\u20130||1\u20130||rowspan=2|Friendly\n|-\n!scope=row|16\n|15 November 2003||29||{{fb|South Africa}}||2\u20131||2\u20131\n|-\n!scope=row|17\n|27 March 2005||rowspan=3|[[Arab Contractors Stadium]], Cairo, Egypt||35||{{fb|Libya|1977}}||1\u20131||rowspan=2|4\u20131||rowspan=2|[[2006 FIFA World Cup qualification (CAF)|2006 FIFA World Cup qualification]]\n|-\n!scope=row|18\n|4 September 2005||38||{{fb|Benin}}||3\u20131\n|-\n!scope=row|19\n|16 November 2005||39||{{fb|Tunisia}}||rowspan=2|1\u20130||1\u20132||Friendly\n|-\n!scope=row|20\n|20 January 2006||Cairo International Stadium, Cairo, Egypt||40||{{fb|Libya|1977}}||3\u20130||[[2006 Africa Cup of Nations]]\n|}\n\n==Post-retirement career==\nAfter his retirement, he turned into analysing [[Premier League]] matches as well as [[UEFA Champions League|Champions league]] matches on [[Al Jazeera Sports]] channels. He also has his own show on [[Al hayat TV]] as well as an on-line show on [[FilGoal]]. He stated that he aims to become a manager after gaining required certificate.\n\n==Managerial career==\n\n===Zamalek===\nAlthough he received numerous offers from teams like [[Paris Saint-Germain Youth Academy]] and Egyptian team [[Al-Masry Club|Al-Masry]] but turned them down. He was appointed as [[Zamalek SC|Zamalek]] head coach after the firing of [[Helmy Toulan]] on 21 January 2014, despite being only 30 years old.<ref name=\"Mido appointed coach of Cairo club Zamalek at age 30.\">{{Cite web \n| title = Mido appointed coach of Cairo club Zamalek at age 30\n| url = https://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/jan/22/mido-appointed-coach-zamalek-spurs\n| work = The Guardian \n| accessdate = 22 January 2014 }}</ref>\nMido led his team to the third place in the [[2013\u201314 Egyptian Premier League]] and secured a place in the [[2015 CAF Confederation Cup]] after a 1\u20130 loss to his rival [[Al Ahly SC|Al-Ahly]], 2\u20131 loss to [[Alexandria]] side [[Smouha Sporting Club|Smouha]] and then a 2\u20130 win over [[Petrojet FC|Petrojet]].<br/>\nMido succeeded to win the [[2014 Egypt Cup|Egypt Cup]] and secure the cup title for the second year in row, by beating [[Smouha Sporting Club|Smouha]] [[2014 Egypt Cup Final|1\u20130]],<ref name=\"egcup14\">{{cite web|title=Zamalek retain Egyptian Cup title|url=http://mtnfootball.com/news/440743/Zamalek-retain-Egyptian-Cup-title|publisher=MTN Football|accessdate=20 August 2014|date=21 July 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140821061449/http://mtnfootball.com/news/440743/Zamalek-retain-Egyptian-Cup-title|archivedate=21 August 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> making him the youngest manager to win a trophy with his team in [[Egypt]].  On 29 July 2014 Mido was replaced by [[Hossam Hassan]] as the manager of Zamalek.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Fenn|first1=Alec|title=Mido sacked by Zamalek|url=http://www.goal.com/en-us/news/84/africa/2014/07/29/4991993/mido-sacked-by-zamalek|publisher=Goal.com|accessdate=20 August 2014|date=29 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Zamalek Youth Academy===\nHe later accepted an offer from [[Zamalek SC|Zamalek]]'s chairman [[Mortada Mansour]] to be the Director of [[Zamalek SC#Youth academy squad|Zamalek Youth Academy]] with appointing his former assistant [[Mohamed Salah (coach)|Mohamed Salah]] as the technical manager of [[Zamalek SC#Youth academy squad|Zamalek Youth Academy]].\nUnder his leadership, The U-16 team won Al Wehda International Championship after defeating FC Steaua Bucure\u0219ti U-16 by a result of 2\u20130 in the final.\n\n===Ismaily===\nOn 15 July 2015, [[Ismaily SC|Ismaily]]'s chairman Mohamed Abo El-Soud announced that Mido will be the manager of the team. He also announced that Ashraf Khedr will be the assistant manager.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.masralarabia.com/sports/%D8%B1%D9%8A%D8%A7%D8%B6%D8%A9-%D9%85%D8%B5%D8%B1%D9%8A%D8%A9/663181-%D8%B5%D9%88%D8%B1%D8%A9-%D9%85%D9%8A%D8%AF%D9%88-%D9%8A%D8%B8%D9%87%D8%B1-%D9%84%D9%84%D9%85%D8%B1%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A3%D9%88%D9%84%D9%89-%D9%81%D9%8A-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A5%D8%B3%D9%85%D8%A7%D8%B9%D9%8A%D9%84%D9%8A|title=\u0635\u0648\u0631\u0629.. \u0645\u064a\u062f\u0648 \u064a\u0638\u0647\u0631 \u0644\u0644\u0645\u0631\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0623\u0648\u0644\u0649 \u0641\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0625\u0633\u0645\u0627\u0639\u064a\u0644\u064a|author=\u0645\u0635\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0631\u0628\u064a\u0629|work=\u0645\u0635\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0631\u0628\u064a\u0629|accessdate=16 July 2015}}</ref> He resigned from his position in 20 December 2015 following a developed\nproblem with the team captain [[Hosny Abd Rabo]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://elfariq.com/news_details_4007_%D9%85%D9%8A%D8%AF%D9%88_%D9%8A%D8%B9%D9%84%D9%86_%D8%A7%D8%B3%D8%AA%D9%82%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AA%D9%87_%D9%85%D9%86_%D8%AA%D8%AF%D8%B1%D9%8A%D8%A8_%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A5%D8%B3%D9%85%D8%A7%D8%B9%D9%8A%D9%84%D9%8A.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=11 February 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151224153923/http://elfariq.com/news_details_4007_%D9%85%D9%8A%D8%AF%D9%88_%D9%8A%D8%B9%D9%84%D9%86_%D8%A7%D8%B3%D8%AA%D9%82%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AA%D9%87_%D9%85%D9%86_%D8%AA%D8%AF%D8%B1%D9%8A%D8%A8_%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A5%D8%B3%D9%85%D8%A7%D8%B9%D9%8A%D9%84%D9%8A.html |archivedate=24 December 2015 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n\n===Return to Zamalek===\nZamalek's chairman [[Mortada Mansour]] announced the return of Mido as the manager of Zamalek, succeeding [[Marcos Paquet\u00e1]] who failed to control the team. He also appointed [[Hazem Emam]] as the general manager and [[Ismail Youssef]] as the technical director. After only one month as a manager, he was fired after a 2\u20130 loss to rivals [[Al Ahly SC|Al Ahly]] in [[Cairo derby]], leading to increase the gap between the two teams to seven points. Later Mortada Mansour said that the board decided to remove Mido from his position after the loss to [[Ismaily SC|Ismaily]], but announcing it was delayed until Cairo Derby is played, to avoid distraction of players.<ref>[http://www.youm7.com/story/2016/2/11/%D9%85%D9%8A%D8%AF%D9%88-%D9%8A%D8%B9%D9%84%D9%86-%D8%AE%D8%B7%D9%88%D8%A7%D8%AA%D9%87-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%82%D8%A7%D8%AF%D9%85%D8%A9-%D8%A8%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AA%D8%AF%D8%B1%D9%8A%D8%A8-%D8%A8%D8%B9%D8%AF-%D8%A5%D8%AC%D8%A7%D8%B2%D8%A9-10-%D8%A3%D9%8A%D8%A7%D9%85/2580518#.Vrzud_l97I]</ref>\n\n===Lierse===\nOn 7 July 2016, [[Lierse S.K.|Lierse]]'s chairman Maged Samy announced the hiring of Mido as a technical adviser for Lierse and [[Wadi Degla SC|Wadi Degla]]. Mido said that he aims to help the club to get promoted to [[Belgian First Division A]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://3robanews.com/sport/47848/%D9%85%D8%B4%D8%A7%D9%87%D9%8A%D8%B1--%D8%A8%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B5%D9%88%D8%B1-%D8%A3%D8%AD%D9%85%D8%AF-%D8%AD%D8%B3%D8%A7%D9%85-%D9%85%D9%8A%D8%AF%D9%88-%D9%85%D8%B3%D8%AA%D8%B4%D8%A7%D8%B1%D8%A7-%D9%81%D9%86%D9%8A%D8%A7-%D9%84%D9%86%D8%A7%D8%AF%D9%8A-%D9%84%D9%8A%D8%B1%D8%B3-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A8%D9%84%D8%AC%D9%8A%D9%83%D9%8A.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=24 July 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160813022816/https://3robanews.com/sport/47848/%D9%85%D8%B4%D8%A7%D9%87%D9%8A%D8%B1--%D8%A8%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B5%D9%88%D8%B1-%D8%A3%D8%AD%D9%85%D8%AF-%D8%AD%D8%B3%D8%A7%D9%85-%D9%85%D9%8A%D8%AF%D9%88-%D9%85%D8%B3%D8%AA%D8%B4%D8%A7%D8%B1%D8%A7-%D9%81%D9%86%D9%8A%D8%A7-%D9%84%D9%86%D8%A7%D8%AF%D9%8A-%D9%84%D9%8A%D8%B1%D8%B3-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A8%D9%84%D8%AC%D9%8A%D9%83%D9%8A.html |archivedate=13 August 2016  }}</ref>\n\n===Wadi Degla===\nOn 8 November 2016, he was appointed as the manager of [[Wadi Degla SC|Wadi Degla]] till the end of [[2016\u201317 Egyptian Premier League|2016\u201317 Season]] following the sack of [[Patrice Carteron]]. Mido also stated that he accepted the job in order to be qualified for [[UEFA A License]] which requires the applicant to be currently managing a team.<ref>[http://new.el-ahly.com/pages/News.aspx?aid=92607]</ref>\n\n===Al Wehda===\n\nOn 17 December 2018, he became technical advisor and caretaker manager at [[Al-Wehda Club (Mecca)|Al Wehda]], after the sacking of [[F\u00e1bio Carille]].<ref>\n[https://www.hiamag.com/\u0647\u0648/\u0631\u064a\u0627\u0636\u0629/903386-\u062a\u0639\u064a\u064a\u0646-\u0645\u064a\u062f\u0648-\u0645\u062f\u0631\u0628\u0627-\u0645\u0624\u0642\u062a\u0627-\u0644\u0646\u0627\u062f\u064a-\u0627\u0644\u0648\u062d\u062f\u0629-\u0627\u0644\u0633\u0639\u0648\u062f\u064a]</ref>\n\n===El Makkasa===\nOn 9 June 2019, Mido was appointed manager of [[Misr Lel Makkasa SC]].<ref>[https://www.kingfut.com/2019/06/09/mido-named-new-misr-el-makkasa-manager/ OFFICIAL: Ahmed Hossam Mido named new Misr El-Makkasa manager], kingfut.com, 9 June 2019</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n\n===Club===\n:Sources:<ref name=\"Hossam ahmed Mido\">{{Cite web | title = Hossam ahmed Mido | url = http://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/football/hossamahmed-mido.html | publisher = Yahoo! Sport | accessdate = 9 July 2007 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071003082447/http://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/football/hossamahmed-mido.html | archivedate = 3 October 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"Hossam Mido\">{{Cite web | title = Hossam Mido | url = http://soccernet.espn.go.com/player/_/id/11741/hossam-mido?cc=5739 | publisher = ESPN Soccernet | accessdate = 11 November 2012}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|National Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|League Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|Continental\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division||Apps||Goals||Apps||Goals||Apps||Goals||Apps||Goals||Apps||Goals\n|-\n|[[Zamalek SC|Zamalek]]\n|1999\u20132000\n|[[Egyptian Premier League]]\n|4||3||0||0||c